15
00:00:43,433 --> 00:00:45,955
And today, I will be talking about Killer Queen Arcade

16
00:00:45,955 --> 00:00:49,597
and how we built a competitive community that spans the entire country as an indie

17
00:00:49,597 --> 00:00:51,619
and what you can learn from what we've done.

18
00:00:51,619 --> 00:00:56,242
This isn't a post-mortem on the game or the community,

19
00:00:56,242 --> 00:00:59,484
but rather a breakdown of a lot of the things that Bumble Bear has done

20
00:00:59,484 --> 00:01:04,888
that I think that can be helpful for other competitive gaming communities to learn from, indie or not.

21
00:01:07,095 --> 00:01:10,296
So, Killer Queen Arcade, for those of you who don't know,

22
00:01:10,296 --> 00:01:13,157
is a five-on-five arcade game created by Josh DeBonis

23
00:01:13,157 --> 00:01:14,077
and Nick Micros in 2013.

24
00:01:14,077 --> 00:01:18,199
Two teams of five players compete against each other

25
00:01:18,199 --> 00:01:20,059
to be the first to accomplish one of three

26
00:01:20,059 --> 00:01:22,840
different victory conditions on a map.

27
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:25,041
An economic victory by collecting 12 berries

28
00:01:25,041 --> 00:01:26,902
scattered around a map and bringing them back

29
00:01:26,902 --> 00:01:28,983
to your hive one at a time.

30
00:01:28,983 --> 00:01:31,444
A military victory by killing the opposing queen

31
00:01:31,444 --> 00:01:32,784
three times in a single game.

32
00:01:34,268 --> 00:01:36,309
or a snail victory by riding a snail

33
00:01:36,309 --> 00:01:37,889
into your own team's goal.

34
00:01:37,889 --> 00:01:40,751
There's a video here that I've linked

35
00:01:40,751 --> 00:01:43,512
that goes into a lot more detail about the game itself.

36
00:01:43,512 --> 00:01:46,533
There's a lot of other mechanics to the game.

37
00:01:46,533 --> 00:01:48,374
For example, there is a queen character

38
00:01:48,374 --> 00:01:50,355
who is different than the other four players.

39
00:01:50,355 --> 00:01:51,835
Workers can become warriors.

40
00:01:51,835 --> 00:01:53,996
There's a speed gate.

41
00:01:53,996 --> 00:01:56,237
So I highly encourage you to watch that video later

42
00:01:56,237 --> 00:01:57,598
if you get the chance.

43
00:01:58,717 --> 00:02:02,961
In roughly half a decade, Killer Queen Arcade has gone from a niche New York arcade game

44
00:02:02,961 --> 00:02:06,505
for hipsters to a niche national arcade game for hipsters.

45
00:02:06,505 --> 00:02:14,234
Today there are over 30 arcade machines available for public play in over 20 states, not counting

46
00:02:14,234 --> 00:02:17,578
the many privately owned cabs that are owned by individuals and corporations.

47
00:02:19,261 --> 00:02:21,403
Every year since 2016, Bumble Bear Games

48
00:02:21,403 --> 00:02:23,764
has organized the National Killer Queen Arcade World

49
00:02:23,764 --> 00:02:27,027
Championship, which is hosted in a different city every year,

50
00:02:27,027 --> 00:02:29,789
bringing in players from around the country

51
00:02:29,789 --> 00:02:33,131
to play to see who is the best team.

52
00:02:33,131 --> 00:02:35,453
In 2016 in Austin, Texas, we had 150 players

53
00:02:35,453 --> 00:02:38,435
come to form over 30 teams.

54
00:02:38,435 --> 00:02:41,397
And last year in 2018, we had Bumble Bash 3,

55
00:02:41,397 --> 00:02:45,300
which was in Portland, Oregon, with 300 players and 60 teams.

56
00:02:46,642 --> 00:02:49,703
And recently, it was just announced that for 2019,

57
00:02:49,703 --> 00:02:53,585
we are going to be in Chattanooga, Tennessee.

58
00:02:53,585 --> 00:02:56,026
So how does Killer Queen build communities?

59
00:02:56,026 --> 00:02:58,127
And more importantly, how can you apply this

60
00:02:58,127 --> 00:02:59,907
to your own game and to your own communities?

61
00:02:59,907 --> 00:03:03,209
So game design builds community.

62
00:03:03,209 --> 00:03:06,250
Killer Queen is designed to bring people together

63
00:03:06,250 --> 00:03:06,670
at its core.

64
00:03:06,670 --> 00:03:08,271
To even play the game,

65
00:03:08,271 --> 00:03:11,012
you need to physically be near a machine.

66
00:03:11,012 --> 00:03:13,033
You have to play together to win as a team.

67
00:03:13,033 --> 00:03:14,614
You can't win by yourself.

68
00:03:14,614 --> 00:03:16,495
Well, you can, but it's pretty hard to.

69
00:03:17,270 --> 00:03:20,133
Local multiplayer means that you have to stand next to your teammates,

70
00:03:20,133 --> 00:03:22,676
and you also have to be in the same space with your competitors too.

71
00:03:22,676 --> 00:03:25,740
And since you're all in the same place together doing the same thing,

72
00:03:25,740 --> 00:03:29,284
you are by definition part of the same community.

73
00:03:29,284 --> 00:03:32,327
The game itself takes all five minutes to learn the basic rules,

74
00:03:32,327 --> 00:03:35,091
but it requires a lot of practice to work together effectively

75
00:03:35,091 --> 00:03:36,272
in order to play competitively.

76
00:03:37,763 --> 00:03:39,225
We also have messaging in the game

77
00:03:39,225 --> 00:03:41,608
that tells players to meet thy neighbors.

78
00:03:41,608 --> 00:03:43,250
This message occurs at the end of the match

79
00:03:43,250 --> 00:03:45,472
and encourages players to meet with each other,

80
00:03:45,472 --> 00:03:47,514
give high fives, congratulatory handshakes,

81
00:03:47,514 --> 00:03:49,296
talk about that match they just played,

82
00:03:49,296 --> 00:03:51,799
or even switch players to start a new game.

83
00:03:51,799 --> 00:03:54,262
It's also possible to add custom messages on the screen

84
00:03:54,262 --> 00:03:56,284
to talk about things like upcoming tournaments,

85
00:03:56,284 --> 00:03:57,906
free plays, meetups, and so forth.

86
00:03:59,460 --> 00:04:00,801
So what can you learn from this?

87
00:04:00,801 --> 00:04:02,562
Think about how the design of your game

88
00:04:02,562 --> 00:04:03,883
or the nature of your game itself

89
00:04:03,883 --> 00:04:06,805
facilitates building a community or building teams.

90
00:04:06,805 --> 00:04:08,146
Have a built-in messaging system

91
00:04:08,146 --> 00:04:09,647
can give subtle messages to players

92
00:04:09,647 --> 00:04:11,608
on how to behave while playing your game,

93
00:04:11,608 --> 00:04:14,890
as well as informing players about the larger community.

94
00:04:14,890 --> 00:04:16,171
If you're looking for other models

95
00:04:16,171 --> 00:04:17,672
of local competitive communities,

96
00:04:17,672 --> 00:04:19,913
look at collectible car games and fighting game communities

97
00:04:19,913 --> 00:04:21,874
or rec leagues like dodgeball and softball.

98
00:04:21,874 --> 00:04:23,776
See how they build their communities

99
00:04:23,776 --> 00:04:26,077
and see what they do to keep players engaged

100
00:04:26,077 --> 00:04:27,178
outside of playing the game.

101
00:04:29,372 --> 00:04:31,353
Streaming and casting help build community.

102
00:04:31,353 --> 00:04:34,174
A lot of the KQ events will stream their games online

103
00:04:34,174 --> 00:04:37,635
to let people watch from wherever they are.

104
00:04:37,635 --> 00:04:39,815
The KQ Arcade cabinet has a separate HDMI port

105
00:04:39,815 --> 00:04:41,556
built into the back of the cab.

106
00:04:41,556 --> 00:04:43,536
You can use either plug into a streaming PC

107
00:04:43,536 --> 00:04:46,257
to put the video online through Twitch

108
00:04:46,257 --> 00:04:48,057
or your streaming platform of your choice,

109
00:04:48,057 --> 00:04:49,998
or you can put it to a TV or a projector.

110
00:04:49,998 --> 00:04:51,478
You can also split that HDMI signal

111
00:04:51,478 --> 00:04:52,979
to put out to multiple streams,

112
00:04:52,979 --> 00:04:54,299
multiple projectors, and so forth.

113
00:04:55,077 --> 00:04:56,999
For bigger tournaments such as Bumble Bash,

114
00:04:56,999 --> 00:04:59,061
we'll also use apps like Restream.io,

115
00:04:59,061 --> 00:05:00,842
which will allow us to show a single stream

116
00:05:00,842 --> 00:05:02,083
on multiple platforms,

117
00:05:02,083 --> 00:05:04,866
or splice multiple machine feeds into one stream.

118
00:05:04,866 --> 00:05:07,908
As you can see in the image over here,

119
00:05:07,908 --> 00:05:10,891
the community has created custom overlays

120
00:05:10,891 --> 00:05:13,253
that show the feed of the game,

121
00:05:13,253 --> 00:05:15,055
a player cam, commentator cam,

122
00:05:15,055 --> 00:05:18,117
as well as showing numbers of sets being won.

123
00:05:18,117 --> 00:05:20,219
I think this one has kill and death ratios

124
00:05:20,219 --> 00:05:21,120
at the bottom also.

125
00:05:22,266 --> 00:05:26,055
This is another example of the one that we had at Bumble Bash in Portland.

126
00:05:28,108 --> 00:05:31,129
In addition, we also have an API that sends out event data,

127
00:05:31,129 --> 00:05:34,150
such as kills, deaths, and berries collected.

128
00:05:34,150 --> 00:05:35,571
Some scenes have taken that data

129
00:05:35,571 --> 00:05:37,711
and created their own stat displays.

130
00:05:37,711 --> 00:05:41,012
So this is an example of one website that has stat tracking

131
00:05:41,012 --> 00:05:42,733
as well as logging event data

132
00:05:42,733 --> 00:05:44,133
based on where you are on the map.

133
00:05:44,133 --> 00:05:47,715
This uses a Raspberry Pi that gets plugged into the cab

134
00:05:47,715 --> 00:05:50,175
and then sends this data to a website.

135
00:05:50,175 --> 00:05:51,596
This website is actually live right now

136
00:05:51,596 --> 00:05:53,216
if you go to bmorekq.com.

137
00:05:53,216 --> 00:05:56,257
Shout outs to the Baltimore KQ community

138
00:05:56,257 --> 00:05:57,378
for putting this together.

139
00:06:00,403 --> 00:06:02,045
So yeah, build in streaming tools

140
00:06:02,045 --> 00:06:04,786
and make it easy to do things like organize tournaments

141
00:06:04,786 --> 00:06:06,467
and show information about your game

142
00:06:06,467 --> 00:06:08,309
and broadcast all of it so that it could be seen

143
00:06:08,309 --> 00:06:11,050
in the best light online and help raise your game's profile.

144
00:06:11,050 --> 00:06:13,092
Spectators can digest what's going on

145
00:06:13,092 --> 00:06:15,753
with the help of color commentators and stat displays

146
00:06:15,753 --> 00:06:17,034
so they can get into your game

147
00:06:17,034 --> 00:06:20,436
without having to actually play the game or even be there.

148
00:06:20,436 --> 00:06:22,157
If you can't provide the tools yourself,

149
00:06:22,157 --> 00:06:24,079
see if you can open up your data for the community

150
00:06:24,079 --> 00:06:26,720
to help you with displaying it.

151
00:06:27,689 --> 00:06:30,551
provide instructions for folks on how to use all of this stuff.

152
00:06:30,551 --> 00:06:32,492
A lot of your fans may not be very technical,

153
00:06:32,492 --> 00:06:33,553
but if you have very clear instructions,

154
00:06:33,553 --> 00:06:37,215
they may be able to figure it out themselves.

155
00:06:37,215 --> 00:06:39,037
Down here is a link to a GitHub repo.

156
00:06:39,037 --> 00:06:42,619
If you want to see an example of the API being used,

157
00:06:42,619 --> 00:06:44,280
this is an app called KQStats.

158
00:06:44,280 --> 00:06:48,483
This was done by Kevin Snyder, as well as a few other folks,

159
00:06:48,483 --> 00:06:49,704
so thank you for doing that.

160
00:06:51,484 --> 00:06:52,944
Events help build communities.

161
00:06:52,944 --> 00:06:56,245
Bumble Bear hosts its national tournament with a trophy

162
00:06:56,245 --> 00:06:57,406
and a custom marquee that it gives

163
00:06:57,406 --> 00:06:59,186
to the winner of a tournament.

164
00:06:59,186 --> 00:07:01,587
Local scenes also host their regular events also.

165
00:07:01,587 --> 00:07:04,988
Because these arcade machines are already in public venues,

166
00:07:04,988 --> 00:07:07,008
we try to partner with them to host events.

167
00:07:07,008 --> 00:07:09,289
So you'll see KQ tournaments and events in bars,

168
00:07:09,289 --> 00:07:12,230
bowling alleys, family fun centers, arcades, barcades,

169
00:07:12,230 --> 00:07:13,410
and even in board game shops.

170
00:07:14,853 --> 00:07:16,614
For tournament play, two commonly used apps

171
00:07:16,614 --> 00:07:19,296
that are used to help organize and manage the tournaments

172
00:07:19,296 --> 00:07:20,897
are SmashGG and Challenge.

173
00:07:20,897 --> 00:07:23,579
We can use these apps to help players register ahead of time,

174
00:07:23,579 --> 00:07:26,821
set up pools and brackets, and post results in real time

175
00:07:26,821 --> 00:07:27,962
online for players to look at.

176
00:07:27,962 --> 00:07:30,684
In addition to doing competitive events,

177
00:07:30,684 --> 00:07:32,885
another kind of event to get players

178
00:07:32,885 --> 00:07:35,687
interested in playing the game without explicitly focusing

179
00:07:35,687 --> 00:07:36,468
on competitive play.

180
00:07:36,908 --> 00:07:39,269
is to do theme competitions or fundraisers

181
00:07:39,269 --> 00:07:40,969
for organizations such as Extra Life.

182
00:07:40,969 --> 00:07:43,690
Despite the fact that KQ is a competitive team game,

183
00:07:43,690 --> 00:07:46,070
scenes have created less competitive events,

184
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:48,671
such as scrambles, where teams are drawn from a hat,

185
00:07:48,671 --> 00:07:50,891
social nights, draft nights,

186
00:07:50,891 --> 00:07:53,092
where queens take turns picking players,

187
00:07:53,092 --> 00:07:55,632
and we have our own version of Battle Royale called Bub G.

188
00:07:55,632 --> 00:07:58,573
Silly things like theme or costume events

189
00:07:58,573 --> 00:08:01,834
like a winter formal create a much more informal environment

190
00:08:01,834 --> 00:08:03,354
and lets people focus on having fun

191
00:08:03,354 --> 00:08:04,534
with and around the game.

192
00:08:07,425 --> 00:08:11,166
So yeah, events build a community, not the other way around.

193
00:08:11,166 --> 00:08:12,666
Organize events as soon as you can.

194
00:08:12,666 --> 00:08:15,506
The first Killer Queen National Tournament was in 2016,

195
00:08:15,506 --> 00:08:17,327
but there were tournaments and meetups held

196
00:08:17,327 --> 00:08:18,827
by the community long before that.

197
00:08:18,827 --> 00:08:21,028
If you feel that your community wants one,

198
00:08:21,028 --> 00:08:23,628
then create one, or if you can't for whatever reason,

199
00:08:23,628 --> 00:08:24,969
help them out in any way you can.

200
00:08:24,969 --> 00:08:27,749
The event itself doesn't have to be a tournament.

201
00:08:27,749 --> 00:08:30,670
It can be a playtest, a mixer, a meetup.

202
00:08:30,670 --> 00:08:32,590
Just do it often and do it frequently.

203
00:08:33,271 --> 00:08:35,672
Don't worry about failure or an event being bad.

204
00:08:35,672 --> 00:08:37,734
You're not trying to plan a fire festival.

205
00:08:37,734 --> 00:08:39,055
You're just giving players a chance.

206
00:08:39,055 --> 00:08:43,317
You're just giving players a chance to play together

207
00:08:43,317 --> 00:08:44,658
in a somewhat organized fashion.

208
00:08:44,658 --> 00:08:47,060
If you do make mistakes, just learn from them

209
00:08:47,060 --> 00:08:48,180
and do better next time.

210
00:08:48,180 --> 00:08:50,602
I'll talk a little bit more about online events

211
00:08:50,602 --> 00:08:52,163
in another slide.

212
00:08:52,163 --> 00:08:53,323
But creating online tournaments

213
00:08:53,323 --> 00:08:55,065
and having everyone meet in a Discord

214
00:08:55,065 --> 00:08:57,046
is a great way to do an event without the need

215
00:08:57,046 --> 00:08:58,767
of having everyone to be in the same place.

216
00:08:59,848 --> 00:09:04,112
One interesting point about planning events is the importance of consistency.

217
00:09:04,112 --> 00:09:10,017
In New York, there is an event every single Friday at NYU in Brooklyn called 5v5 Fridays.

218
00:09:10,017 --> 00:09:12,820
It's hosted by one of the professors, Charles J. Pratt.

219
00:09:12,820 --> 00:09:15,683
He noticed that by being consistently every single Friday,

220
00:09:15,683 --> 00:09:18,545
players can always just show up whenever they have a free Friday

221
00:09:18,545 --> 00:09:21,768
as opposed to having to plan for the event that only happens once a month,

222
00:09:21,768 --> 00:09:24,030
which lessens the hassle of having to come to play the game.

223
00:09:24,611 --> 00:09:26,072
You'll have regulars that come there every week,

224
00:09:26,072 --> 00:09:27,272
but you'll also have access to people

225
00:09:27,272 --> 00:09:28,713
who may show up every two weeks,

226
00:09:28,713 --> 00:09:30,254
or maybe only just once a month.

227
00:09:30,254 --> 00:09:33,416
If you have an individual player-based game,

228
00:09:33,416 --> 00:09:35,597
but you wanna have folks competing in events like teams,

229
00:09:35,597 --> 00:09:37,298
there are ways to organize that too.

230
00:09:37,298 --> 00:09:40,220
At Bumble Bash 3, we created an Olympic-style

231
00:09:40,220 --> 00:09:42,061
scoring system called the Dang System

232
00:09:42,061 --> 00:09:43,822
that gave points per player.

233
00:09:43,822 --> 00:09:45,863
At the end of the tournament, we grouped players by region

234
00:09:45,863 --> 00:09:48,004
and added the points together of the top 17 players

235
00:09:48,004 --> 00:09:50,245
of each region to determine the winner.

236
00:09:50,245 --> 00:09:52,467
The winning city got an arcade machine.

237
00:09:55,388 --> 00:09:57,828
Engaging with the community builds community.

238
00:09:57,828 --> 00:10:01,569
Bumble Bear travels across the country to KQ events

239
00:10:01,569 --> 00:10:03,310
to talk to players and fans and play with them.

240
00:10:03,310 --> 00:10:05,870
Bumble Bear will also bring with them new maps,

241
00:10:05,870 --> 00:10:07,351
new game modes to test out,

242
00:10:07,351 --> 00:10:09,691
and answer questions about Killer Queen.

243
00:10:09,691 --> 00:10:12,112
Every year there's also a state of Killer Queen announcement

244
00:10:12,112 --> 00:10:13,912
where they talk about the upcoming roadmap and plans.

245
00:10:13,912 --> 00:10:19,074
And when I talk about engaging with the community,

246
00:10:19,074 --> 00:10:22,515
Nick and Josh really, really engage with the community.

247
00:10:23,988 --> 00:10:26,270
So this was recently at the South Florida,

248
00:10:26,270 --> 00:10:27,571
there was a Kale Green event there.

249
00:10:27,571 --> 00:10:30,713
That's Nick in the, I think, hot tub being fed a steak.

250
00:10:30,713 --> 00:10:30,873
So yeah.

251
00:10:35,429 --> 00:10:37,791
Travel to events to promote the game.

252
00:10:37,791 --> 00:10:39,672
Make yourselves accessible to the community

253
00:10:39,672 --> 00:10:41,653
for direct conversations and feedback,

254
00:10:41,653 --> 00:10:43,634
and engage only as much as you're comfortable.

255
00:10:43,634 --> 00:10:46,216
Attending community events legitimizes those events

256
00:10:46,216 --> 00:10:48,397
in the player's eyes and encourages people to attend

257
00:10:48,397 --> 00:10:49,138
and builds goodwill.

