00:10:49,138 --> 00:10:52,400
You should also do regular testing with your community.

259
00:10:52,400 --> 00:10:53,261
Try out ideas.

260
00:10:53,261 --> 00:10:54,902
Keep good ones, throw away the rest.

261
00:10:54,902 --> 00:10:56,062
And even with your bad ideas,

262
00:10:56,062 --> 00:10:57,103
let your fans have fun with it,

263
00:10:57,103 --> 00:10:58,224
and you never know what would happen.

264
00:10:59,144 --> 00:11:00,686
We tried game modes all the time.

265
00:11:00,686 --> 00:11:02,487
For a long time, there was a mode in Killer Queen

266
00:11:02,487 --> 00:11:06,250
that had scorpions, which having scorpions

267
00:11:06,250 --> 00:11:09,492
and bears and bees, I thought was a terrible idea,

268
00:11:09,492 --> 00:11:11,013
but people liked it and whatever.

269
00:11:11,013 --> 00:11:14,516
Keep the game fresh, it keeps the game fresh

270
00:11:14,516 --> 00:11:16,698
and people keep talking about it.

271
00:11:16,698 --> 00:11:18,059
Turn these tests into an event.

272
00:11:18,059 --> 00:11:21,021
If you can't travel to other scenes, play online.

273
00:11:21,021 --> 00:11:23,283
Host and play with your fans and players once a week.

274
00:11:23,563 --> 00:11:28,788
do an AMA, blog, you can even do things like having regular tests where the highest scoring

275
00:11:28,788 --> 00:11:33,092
player that week or month gets to challenge the designers and developers.

276
00:11:33,092 --> 00:11:35,935
And whatever you do, put it online and stream it.

277
00:11:38,255 --> 00:11:41,476
If there's one thing that you should take away from this talk,

278
00:11:41,476 --> 00:11:44,357
it should be that aside from designing a very compelling and engaging game,

279
00:11:44,357 --> 00:11:48,979
Bumble Bear's accessibility and engagement with its very, very active community

280
00:11:48,979 --> 00:11:51,941
is a key factor to the success of Killer Queen.

281
00:11:51,941 --> 00:11:54,642
Being part of your community gives you the opportunity to get insight

282
00:11:54,642 --> 00:11:56,583
about what the community wants to see.

283
00:11:57,094 --> 00:11:59,275
as well as instills confidence that the developers

284
00:11:59,275 --> 00:12:00,717
will be able to shape the game into something

285
00:12:00,717 --> 00:12:01,657
that people will want to play.

286
00:12:01,657 --> 00:12:03,699
And even if Bumble Bear can't do it themselves,

287
00:12:03,699 --> 00:12:06,361
sometimes creating the opportunity for the community

288
00:12:06,361 --> 00:12:09,884
to help fill in those gaps can be still just as effective.

289
00:12:09,884 --> 00:12:11,786
Having said that, I don't want you to walk away

290
00:12:11,786 --> 00:12:13,828
from this talk thinking that Bumble Bear knocks it out

291
00:12:13,828 --> 00:12:15,089
of the park every single time.

292
00:12:15,089 --> 00:12:17,351
At one point, we came up with the idea

293
00:12:17,351 --> 00:12:19,332
of establishing a membership-based

294
00:12:19,332 --> 00:12:20,693
National Killer Queen League.

295
00:12:21,277 --> 00:12:23,678
You pay a fee, you get some cool stuff out of it,

296
00:12:23,678 --> 00:12:25,480
and you help fund an organization dedicated

297
00:12:25,480 --> 00:12:28,122
to managing a competitive National Killer Queen League.

298
00:12:28,122 --> 00:12:32,225
I'm not gonna get into the details of what it all entailed,

299
00:12:32,225 --> 00:12:34,466
but long story short, it was not well received

300
00:12:34,466 --> 00:12:37,008
by the community for various reasons.

301
00:12:37,008 --> 00:12:38,810
This is one of the posts that was on the Facebook page

302
00:12:38,810 --> 00:12:39,730
in response.

303
00:12:39,730 --> 00:12:42,652
This was a situation where we got insight

304
00:12:42,652 --> 00:12:44,274
that the community wanted something,

305
00:12:44,274 --> 00:12:46,235
but we didn't create what they actually needed,

306
00:12:46,235 --> 00:12:48,297
and we executed very poorly.

307
00:12:48,297 --> 00:12:50,818
And as a result, the community told us how they felt.

308
00:12:51,982 --> 00:12:54,403
So we realized the idea wasn't quite the right fit,

309
00:12:54,403 --> 00:12:56,505
so we wound up shelving it.

310
00:12:56,505 --> 00:13:00,228
So merch and fan art built communities.

311
00:13:00,228 --> 00:13:01,209
Merch is merch.

312
00:13:01,209 --> 00:13:04,531
People like to buy merch to support the things they love.

313
00:13:04,531 --> 00:13:06,473
Originally, Bumble Beer had an Amazon store,

314
00:13:06,473 --> 00:13:08,594
but we decided to create our own storefront.

315
00:13:08,594 --> 00:13:10,196
We had issues with people making cheaper,

316
00:13:10,196 --> 00:13:11,897
counterfeit versions of our stuff

317
00:13:11,897 --> 00:13:13,258
and selling it on our product pages.

318
00:13:13,258 --> 00:13:15,600
So it was just easier for us to take our merchandise

319
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:17,581
completely off Amazon and just do our own thing.

320
00:13:18,225 --> 00:13:21,813
If you don't want to deal with your own inventory and stuff, and I don't blame you, there are

321
00:13:21,813 --> 00:13:24,559
companies that you can partner with, such as Fangamer or Sanshi.

322
00:13:27,258 --> 00:13:29,440
In addition to Bumble Bear created merch,

323
00:13:29,440 --> 00:13:30,961
Bumble Bear encourages the community

324
00:13:30,961 --> 00:13:32,423
to create their own merch,

325
00:13:32,423 --> 00:13:35,145
and express themselves in the universe of Killer Queen.

326
00:13:35,145 --> 00:13:36,967
It gives the fans a chance to contribute

327
00:13:36,967 --> 00:13:38,649
to something that they already love.

328
00:13:38,649 --> 00:13:41,172
And our fans make some really amazing things.

329
00:13:41,172 --> 00:13:44,034
From picture frames, t-shirts, posters.

330
00:13:44,034 --> 00:13:45,856
I'm actually wearing a fan created shirt.

331
00:13:45,856 --> 00:13:47,898
This was done by one of the Chicago players,

332
00:13:47,898 --> 00:13:48,639
Michael Sparza.

333
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:52,982
And yeah, we have one rule for fan merch.

334
00:13:52,982 --> 00:13:55,223
Don't directly rip off the art from the game.

335
00:13:55,223 --> 00:13:56,964
It should be transformative.

336
00:13:56,964 --> 00:13:58,465
Reinterpret the art in your own way.

337
00:13:58,465 --> 00:14:02,066
So all these three things were created by our fans

338
00:14:02,066 --> 00:14:03,707
for either events or for teams.

339
00:14:03,707 --> 00:14:06,028
The calendar in the middle was actually

340
00:14:06,028 --> 00:14:08,310
a fundraising project for Girls Who Code.

341
00:14:08,310 --> 00:14:12,792
Bumbleblair also makes our source assets available

342
00:14:12,792 --> 00:14:14,933
for fans to use, which I didn't think was a crazy thing

343
00:14:14,933 --> 00:14:16,594
until I told people and they thought I was crazy.

344
00:14:17,680 --> 00:14:18,901
If you dig around the press kit,

345
00:14:18,901 --> 00:14:20,582
you will find player sprites,

346
00:14:20,582 --> 00:14:22,604
as well as some quality versions of our logo.

347
00:14:22,604 --> 00:14:24,525
And a lot of people will use these assets

348
00:14:24,525 --> 00:14:25,866
for the basis of fan art,

349
00:14:25,866 --> 00:14:27,948
or for graphics to use for their posters, t-shirts,

350
00:14:27,948 --> 00:14:29,409
and all sorts of other things.

351
00:14:29,409 --> 00:14:31,930
The image on the right over here

352
00:14:31,930 --> 00:14:34,212
is an example of someone using one of our sprites

353
00:14:34,212 --> 00:14:36,334
and customizing it for their posters.

354
00:14:36,334 --> 00:14:37,995
All these other images here are fan art

355
00:14:37,995 --> 00:14:39,896
and event posters that the community has made.

356
00:14:39,896 --> 00:14:42,318
And you'll be very surprised that, you know,

357
00:14:42,318 --> 00:14:44,840
your fans may be able to make art better than you.

358
00:14:47,150 --> 00:14:49,192
In addition to encouraging folks to create and sell

359
00:14:49,192 --> 00:14:52,415
fan-created merchandise, Bumble Bear takes it a step further

360
00:14:52,415 --> 00:14:54,917
and will actually sell a community,

361
00:14:54,917 --> 00:14:57,259
or approved community-created merch on its own online store

362
00:14:57,259 --> 00:15:00,621
for a cut of the sale plus cost of shipping and handling.

363
00:15:00,621 --> 00:15:04,064
Those posters over here are created by,

364
00:15:04,064 --> 00:15:07,567
also I think a Chicago player, John Doon.

365
00:15:08,098 --> 00:15:09,760
and they're gorgeous and they're available

366
00:15:09,760 --> 00:15:12,161
on the store right now if you wanna buy them.

367
00:15:12,161 --> 00:15:14,443
We'll also do the same thing at events like Bumble Bash

368
00:15:14,443 --> 00:15:16,445
where we have a merch table where fans can sell

369
00:15:16,445 --> 00:15:17,826
their stuff there for a percentage cut.

370
00:15:17,826 --> 00:15:20,287
By keeping things to a merch table at events,

371
00:15:20,287 --> 00:15:21,588
you can see all the kinds of cool things

372
00:15:21,588 --> 00:15:23,350
that people are making and it keeps all the merch

373
00:15:23,350 --> 00:15:24,691
selling in one area at a venue.

374
00:15:25,311 --> 00:15:28,316
The only other note I have is that you should be careful about tax laws,

375
00:15:28,316 --> 00:15:31,762
as you're conducting business in some states, and they may consider that vending,

376
00:15:31,762 --> 00:15:35,428
and therefore you have to deduct or collect sales tax for it.

377
00:15:35,428 --> 00:15:38,674
I'm not a lawyer, I'm not an accountant, I'm just letting you know ahead of time.

378
00:15:40,293 --> 00:15:43,514
So yeah, there are caveats to making your own merch,

379
00:15:43,514 --> 00:15:46,034
but like I said, there are companies that can do it for you.

380
00:15:46,034 --> 00:15:48,855
Either way, it's definitely something you should do.

381
00:15:48,855 --> 00:15:51,476
Encourage people to create fan art,

382
00:15:51,476 --> 00:15:53,356
do competitions, do contests with it.

383
00:15:53,356 --> 00:15:56,297
And if you're as crazy as Bumble Bear,

384
00:15:56,297 --> 00:15:58,317
sell merch actually created by your friends,

385
00:15:58,317 --> 00:15:59,198
or by your fans.

386
00:15:59,718 --> 00:16:02,982
And if you're worried about things like rip-offs and stuff like that,

387
00:16:02,982 --> 00:16:06,848
in my time at Bumble Bear, I found it very effective to tell people

388
00:16:06,848 --> 00:16:09,331
to have to make their art more transformative.

389
00:16:09,331 --> 00:16:12,355
It challenges them to make something better without saying no,

390
00:16:12,355 --> 00:16:14,498
and in the end, they're likely going to make something cool

391
00:16:14,498 --> 00:16:16,681
and something that you may not have thought about yourself.

392
00:16:19,064 --> 00:16:21,326
Sponsors can help build communities.

