00:21:06,234 --> 00:21:06,954
you're behind.

513
00:21:08,999 --> 00:21:11,000
Champions help build communities.

514
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,302
Find your super fans as you build your communities

515
00:21:13,302 --> 00:21:14,622
and enable them to be your champions.

516
00:21:14,622 --> 00:21:16,604
For Killer Queen, these were the ones

517
00:21:16,604 --> 00:21:18,305
who helped organize the first local tournaments

518
00:21:18,305 --> 00:21:19,545
in different cities.

519
00:21:19,545 --> 00:21:21,907
They were the ones that created all the cool merch

520
00:21:21,907 --> 00:21:23,908
that streamed our game, that did commentary,

521
00:21:23,908 --> 00:21:25,469
that got new players into the game.

522
00:21:25,469 --> 00:21:27,510
We even created an award for this,

523
00:21:27,510 --> 00:21:29,971
the Charles J. Pratt Community Service Award,

524
00:21:29,971 --> 00:21:33,773
which was won in the first year by Charles J. Pratt.

525
00:21:34,934 --> 00:21:36,036
But reward your champions.

526
00:21:36,036 --> 00:21:39,480
If you have an upcoming game, give them keys to give away.

527
00:21:39,480 --> 00:21:42,825
Give them assets if they ask for them to make art and merch.

528
00:21:42,825 --> 00:21:44,407
Ask for their feedback.

529
00:21:44,407 --> 00:21:47,051
Ask for them to help organize an event,

530
00:21:47,051 --> 00:21:49,274
and ask them to help you promote your game to new fans.

531
00:21:50,135 --> 00:21:53,517
Another thing that we did at Bumble Bear was that we had a small committee of fans that

532
00:21:53,517 --> 00:21:56,119
we talked to about upcoming events and ideas.

533
00:21:56,119 --> 00:21:59,141
If you have an idea you want to do with the community, it's always good to have a small

534
00:21:59,141 --> 00:22:02,384
group of people to test it with first before you go forward with something.

535
00:22:02,384 --> 00:22:07,508
They can help embrace an idea or an event, they can help hype up the community, and in

536
00:22:07,508 --> 00:22:09,769
general they just help make good ideas great.

537
00:22:10,602 --> 00:22:13,547
Partnering with a streamer or YouTube was something

538
00:22:13,547 --> 00:22:15,209
that we always wanted to do,

539
00:22:15,209 --> 00:22:16,551
but given the nature of our game,

540
00:22:16,551 --> 00:22:19,215
this makes it kind of difficult.

541
00:22:19,215 --> 00:22:20,757
Luckily, most of you aren't making arcade games,

542
00:22:20,757 --> 00:22:23,822
so that shouldn't be an excuse for you guys.

543
00:22:23,822 --> 00:22:24,303
Or for you all.

544
00:22:25,228 --> 00:22:28,050
Other communities can help build your community.

545
00:22:28,050 --> 00:22:30,151
Killer Queen attracts all sorts of players

546
00:22:30,151 --> 00:22:31,152
looking for competition.

547
00:22:31,152 --> 00:22:33,293
We have folks from the fighting game community,

548
00:22:33,293 --> 00:22:35,774
speed runners, recreational league, dodge ball,

549
00:22:35,774 --> 00:22:39,096
softball players, who are just attractive to competition

550
00:22:39,096 --> 00:22:40,137
and the competitiveness of KQ.

551
00:22:40,137 --> 00:22:43,318
It would be smart to engage or partner with other communities

552
00:22:43,318 --> 00:22:45,580
to cross-promote events and games.

553
00:22:45,580 --> 00:22:47,441
At Bumble Bash, we will actually host games

554
00:22:47,441 --> 00:22:48,902
made by other indies.

555
00:22:48,902 --> 00:22:52,904
So the image here is a game called Death Ball Arcade

556
00:22:52,904 --> 00:22:54,445
by Tony Halber, who's the one playing it.

557
00:22:55,158 --> 00:22:59,501
It's worth looking into other competitive gaming communities and think about the opportunity

558
00:22:59,501 --> 00:23:02,443
for collaboration on events or promotion.

559
00:23:02,443 --> 00:23:04,784
In this situation, I think a rising tide lifts all boats.

560
00:23:06,920 --> 00:23:09,142
Formalized communication builds communities.

561
00:23:09,142 --> 00:23:10,883
Clear communication builds trust,

562
00:23:10,883 --> 00:23:13,466
prevents confusion and uncertainty about your game.

563
00:23:13,466 --> 00:23:14,527
State of the game announcements,

564
00:23:14,527 --> 00:23:16,829
public roadmaps, and blogs are all very important.

565
00:23:16,829 --> 00:23:21,033
This is the Trello board for Killer Queen Black,

566
00:23:21,033 --> 00:23:23,735
which is the upcoming Killer Queen title

567
00:23:23,735 --> 00:23:25,236
coming out for the PC and Switch.

568
00:23:26,177 --> 00:23:27,358
please buy it when it comes out.

569
00:23:27,358 --> 00:23:29,919
They did a pretty good job of showing their work

570
00:23:29,919 --> 00:23:31,800
with a public Trello, showing release notes,

571
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:34,121
upcoming development, outstanding work, and so forth.

572
00:23:34,121 --> 00:23:36,523
With all forms of formal communication,

573
00:23:36,523 --> 00:23:38,984
keep it simple, straightforward, and consistent,

574
00:23:38,984 --> 00:23:40,945
so it's not a pain in the butt to maintain.

575
00:23:40,945 --> 00:23:43,627
And if things change, be sure to update it.

576
00:23:43,627 --> 00:23:47,449
Also, try not to update or make any major changes

577
00:23:47,449 --> 00:23:49,230
on your game before a tournament,

578
00:23:49,230 --> 00:23:50,571
otherwise you're gonna piss off your fans.

